1
00:01:07,167 --> 00:01:08,500
(engine starts up)

2
00:01:46,500 --> 00:01:48,267
Dad, are we there yet?

3
00:01:49,733 --> 00:01:52,100
Not quite, sweetheart.
We'll be home before long.

4
00:01:56,600 --> 00:01:58,667
You guys want to sing
to pass the time?

5
00:01:58,700 --> 00:02:00,733
-Yeah?
-Hooray!

6
00:02:00,767 --> 00:02:02,233
Hey, you wanna sing, Max?

7
00:02:02,267 --> 00:02:04,467
Yeah? Steven, you wanna sing?

8
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:06,800
-I can sing.
-Yeah. Do you wanna sing?

9
00:02:06,833 --> 00:02:08,467
-Yeah.
-Okay.

10
00:02:08,500 --> 00:02:12,633
* (all singing London Bridge 
 is Falling Down ) *

11
00:02:22,933 --> 00:02:25,567
* (singing continues) *

12
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:31,333
(smashing)

13
00:02:31,367 --> 00:02:33,467
(brakes screeching)

14
00:02:33,500 --> 00:02:35,067
(crashing)

15
00:02:54,267 --> 00:02:56,667
I'm Dr. Klein. Uh, you are...

16
00:02:56,700 --> 00:02:59,367
I'm Len Jordan,
uh, Luke's brother.

17
00:02:59,400 --> 00:03:01,100
My wife, Ruth.

18
00:03:01,133 --> 00:03:02,300
Mr. and Mrs. Jordan,

19
00:03:02,333 --> 00:03:05,967
I'm not quite sure
how to say this, but...

20
00:03:06,067 --> 00:03:08,533
...both Luke and Helen, as well
as their daughter Jennifer

21
00:03:08,567 --> 00:03:10,333
-didn't survive the crash.
-(gasps)

22
00:03:12,933 --> 00:03:15,333
What about the boys?
What about Max and Steven?

23
00:03:15,367 --> 00:03:17,267
Well, Max is undergoing
some routine tests

24
00:03:17,300 --> 00:03:19,067
but it looks as though
he's going to be fine.

25
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:23,467
Steven, on the other hand,
is in critical shape.

26
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:25,467
He suffered massive
cranial damage

27
00:03:25,500 --> 00:03:27,633
-and he's currently comatose.
-(gasps)

28
00:03:36,067 --> 00:03:37,500
(sobs)

29
00:03:39,833 --> 00:03:41,500
Is he going to live?

30
00:03:41,533 --> 00:03:44,600
Well, the next 48 hours are
going to be very critical but...

31
00:03:44,633 --> 00:03:45,700
if he does survive,

32
00:03:45,733 --> 00:03:47,700
he's going to need
multiple operations.

33
00:03:48,967 --> 00:03:50,633
There's also the chance

34
00:03:50,667 --> 00:03:52,533
that Steven might be
mentally impaired

35
00:03:52,567 --> 00:03:54,100
as a result of his injuries.

36
00:03:54,133 --> 00:03:56,300
I'm afraid he's going
to need long-term

37
00:03:56,333 --> 00:03:58,067
possibly even permanent, care.

38
00:03:59,467 --> 00:04:00,733
Dr. Klein: I'm very sorry...

39
00:04:02,733 --> 00:04:05,400
Well, I, uh,
better get back and see them.

40
00:04:05,433 --> 00:04:07,667
I'll let you know as soon as
there's any change.

41
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:10,167
(receding footsteps)

42
00:04:11,633 --> 00:04:15,933
(distraught sobbing)

43
00:04:23,067 --> 00:04:24,467
(thunder rumbles)

44
00:04:24,500 --> 00:04:26,833
(typing)

45
00:04:31,367 --> 00:04:32,500
Ruthie!

46
00:04:33,667 --> 00:04:34,667
Ruthie!

47
00:04:36,733 --> 00:04:37,967
I'm coming.

48
00:04:46,433 --> 00:04:47,867
(typing)

49
00:04:47,900 --> 00:04:49,967
Congratulations, sweetheart.

50
00:04:50,067 --> 00:04:51,667
Oh, I couldn't have done it
without you.

51
00:04:51,700 --> 00:04:52,733
(gushes)

52
00:04:54,267 --> 00:04:56,233
So, now what do you think?

53
00:04:56,267 --> 00:04:58,633
Well, I think it's brilliant.

54
00:04:58,667 --> 00:05:00,100
-Really?
-Yep.

55
00:05:00,900 --> 00:05:02,367
In fact,
I think it's so brilliant

56
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:05,067
Harry's only gonna make me
rewrite it five times.

57
00:05:05,067 --> 00:05:07,067
(laughs)
Well, we hate him.

58
00:05:07,067 --> 00:05:09,133
-Yes...
-(doorbell rings)

59
00:05:09,167 --> 00:05:10,233
Now, who could that be?

60
00:05:10,267 --> 00:05:11,567
(chair creaks loudly)

61
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:17,367
(thunder rumbles)

62
00:05:20,100 --> 00:05:21,867
Ruth: Oh, for goodness sake.

63
00:05:21,900 --> 00:05:23,100
It's Max.

64
00:05:23,133 --> 00:05:24,900
(door opens)

65
00:05:24,933 --> 00:05:26,933
Ruth: Honey, look at you...

66
00:05:28,233 --> 00:05:30,200
Come in. Take your coat off.

67
00:05:30,233 --> 00:05:31,833
Maxwell, my boy.

68
00:05:31,867 --> 00:05:33,633
You're just in time
to help us celebrate.

69
00:05:33,667 --> 00:05:35,667
Take your coat off and sit down.

70
00:05:39,067 --> 00:05:40,400
So, we're celebrating.

71
00:05:41,433 --> 00:05:43,067
You must've finished
your new novel.

72
00:05:43,100 --> 00:05:44,467
Len: You bet your boots, I did.

73
00:05:45,433 --> 00:05:47,933
Great. What's it called?

74
00:05:49,367 --> 00:05:51,200
(both chuckle)

75
00:05:51,233 --> 00:05:53,133
Very funny, Max.

76
00:05:53,167 --> 00:05:54,267
"Very funny."

77
00:05:55,467 --> 00:05:56,567
So it's a comedy?

78
00:05:56,600 --> 00:05:58,867
Oh, "a comedy."
Would you listen to him?

79
00:05:58,900 --> 00:06:00,067
(both chuckle)

80
00:06:02,500 --> 00:06:04,067
Max, is everything all right?

81
00:06:08,633 --> 00:06:10,600
Max: "Is everything all right?"

82
00:06:10,633 --> 00:06:12,133
(thunder rumbles)

83
00:06:12,167 --> 00:06:14,067
(giggles dryly)

84
00:06:16,633 --> 00:06:17,633
Well...

85
00:06:20,300 --> 00:06:21,333
...why wouldn't it be?

86
00:06:24,233 --> 00:06:25,500
You know...

87
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:30,500
There's something I've been
meaning to talk to you about.

88
00:06:30,533 --> 00:06:32,933
(thunder rumbles)

89
00:06:35,167 --> 00:06:38,067
(multiple gunshots)

90
00:07:07,600 --> 00:07:09,500
Man: I'm always amazed at people
that seem to know

91
00:07:09,533 --> 00:07:11,400
the right thing to say
at a time like this.

92
00:07:12,567 --> 00:07:13,933
I don't know if there are
any words that can

93
00:07:13,967 --> 00:07:16,967
really make sense out of
what's happened.

94
00:07:17,067 --> 00:07:21,533
So... I'd like to borrow
from Uncle Len's writing...

95
00:07:22,767 --> 00:07:23,867
...to eulogize them.

96
00:07:25,867 --> 00:07:28,267
"Death is never cruel
to its recipient.

97
00:07:29,433 --> 00:07:32,833
But to those who are left
with a piercing memory,

98
00:07:32,867 --> 00:07:35,433
a sting that soon softens
into the numbness..."

99
00:07:50,100 --> 00:07:53,167
Uncle Len, I'll never understand
why this happened...

100
00:07:54,900 --> 00:07:57,067
...but I want you to know that
in my heart...

101
00:08:00,500 --> 00:08:01,900
...I forgive you.

102
00:08:13,800 --> 00:08:15,100
Stu: Thanks for having us,
sweetheart.

103
00:08:15,133 --> 00:08:16,133
Oh, of course, Stu.

104
00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:19,633
-Whatever we can do for you.
-Oh, thank you.

105
00:08:19,667 --> 00:08:20,867
That's very nice.

106
00:08:20,900 --> 00:08:22,533
Remember, we're family
and we're here for you.

107
00:08:22,567 --> 00:08:25,933
-You take care, Liv.
-Oh, Stu, thanks for coming.

108
00:08:25,967 --> 00:08:27,367
-Very nice to meet you.
-Nice to meet you.

109
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:28,433
-Bye bye.
-Bye bye, now.

110
00:08:28,467 --> 00:08:29,467
Stu: Bye.

111
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:32,167
"Liv".
I hate that name.

112
00:08:32,200 --> 00:08:34,067
Why did he call me that?

113
00:08:34,067 --> 00:08:36,167
You know,
she didn't bother me so much,

114
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:38,167
it was just the...
the friends she brought along.

115
00:08:38,200 --> 00:08:39,633
-Oh, Tess--
-The two friends seemed kinda

116
00:08:39,667 --> 00:08:42,067
-nice to me.
-Oh, nice, fabulous people.

117
00:08:42,067 --> 00:08:44,067
I just hope Macy's isn't
missing that mannequin.

118
00:08:44,067 --> 00:08:45,700
-Oh, gosh.
-(laughs)

119
00:08:45,733 --> 00:08:46,967
Yeah, we do a lot
of weird things

120
00:08:47,067 --> 00:08:49,067
in our lives but
a post funeral party

121
00:08:49,067 --> 00:08:51,367
has got to be the strangest.

122
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:53,433
Well, you know,
it's a good excuse to have

123
00:08:53,467 --> 00:08:54,500
a few drinks.

124
00:08:54,533 --> 00:08:55,667
You don't need an excuse.

125
00:08:55,700 --> 00:08:57,133
-Hey--
-I mean,

126
00:08:57,167 --> 00:08:59,200
all those people needing to
tell us everything that they

127
00:08:59,233 --> 00:09:01,833
really wanted to say to Uncle
Len but never got a chance to.

128
00:09:01,867 --> 00:09:03,667
Well, you know,
people need closure.

129
00:09:03,700 --> 00:09:05,367
It's their way
of tying things up

130
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:06,933
so they can get on
with their lives.

131
00:09:06,967 --> 00:09:09,200
No extra baggage,
no unresolved issues.

132
00:09:09,233 --> 00:09:10,900
Mm, I love it when you

133
00:09:10,933 --> 00:09:12,133
-talk dirty like that.
-Uncle Len...

134
00:09:12,167 --> 00:09:13,633
Why would he do something
like this?

135
00:09:13,667 --> 00:09:15,300
I mean, him, of all people?

136
00:09:15,333 --> 00:09:17,100
Well he did suffer
from depression.

137
00:09:17,133 --> 00:09:18,167
Yeah..

138
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:19,800
Tess,
it couldn't have been that bad.

139
00:09:19,833 --> 00:09:22,567
Tess: Well, sometimes the downs
can be so intense

140
00:09:22,600 --> 00:09:24,867
that they can push even
nonviolent people to extremes.

141
00:09:24,900 --> 00:09:27,067
Tess, you knew him...
and do you really think

142
00:09:27,067 --> 00:09:28,633
he could've done something
like this?

143
00:09:28,667 --> 00:09:31,333
Well, no one really
could've known.

144
00:09:31,367 --> 00:09:33,667
-You know, it's--
-What did the note say?

145
00:09:33,700 --> 00:09:35,500
If you don't mind me asking.

146
00:09:35,533 --> 00:09:36,633
It said:

147
00:09:37,833 --> 00:09:39,767
"In a perfect world there is

148
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:41,067
no illness,

149
00:09:41,100 --> 00:09:42,200
no suffering,

150
00:09:42,233 --> 00:09:43,233
no pain.

151
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:45,533
No disappointment.

152
00:09:47,133 --> 00:09:48,800
No fear.
No emptiness.

153
00:09:51,533 --> 00:09:53,467
But this world is not
a perfect one.

154
00:09:55,067 --> 00:09:56,667
And I am not
who I appear to be."

155
00:10:15,333 --> 00:10:16,733
(pants lightly)

156
00:10:19,633 --> 00:10:20,833
Woman: Are you coming to bed?

157
00:10:23,100 --> 00:10:24,067
Yeah...

158
00:10:48,633 --> 00:10:49,767
Good night.

159
00:10:57,233 --> 00:10:58,533
Do you feel like talking?

160
00:11:00,167 --> 00:11:01,233
No.

161
00:11:08,700 --> 00:11:10,067
I love you.

162
00:11:31,067 --> 00:11:33,600
(siren sounds in distance)

163
00:12:02,267 --> 00:12:03,567
God bless you.

164
00:12:12,367 --> 00:12:13,867
-Hi.
-Hi, boss.

165
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:14,933
How ya holding' up?

166
00:12:14,967 --> 00:12:16,533
Good, good.
Thanks for being there.

167
00:12:16,567 --> 00:12:19,067
Oh, please... I mean, you should
have taken the day off.

168
00:12:19,067 --> 00:12:21,167
No choice. We got too much
going on around here.

169
00:12:21,200 --> 00:12:23,767
Oh, yeah. The lovely
and talented Stu Fishman

170
00:12:23,800 --> 00:12:25,733
-wants to see us when we get in.
-No.

171
00:12:25,767 --> 00:12:27,633
-Are you in?
-Yeah...

172
00:12:27,667 --> 00:12:29,533
I'm sure he just wants
to give you the old:

173
00:12:29,567 --> 00:12:30,967
"We're really sorry about
the tragedy.

174
00:12:31,067 --> 00:12:33,333
We hope this won't affect
your work performance?" bit.

175
00:12:33,367 --> 00:12:34,400
I mean, let's face it.

176
00:12:34,433 --> 00:12:36,200
The guy's got
a gold-plated heart.

177
00:12:36,233 --> 00:12:39,300
-Are you ready for these?
-I just saw the weirdest thing.

178
00:12:39,333 --> 00:12:41,500
On my way in,
there was this old guy...

179
00:12:41,533 --> 00:12:42,533
A homeless guy.

180
00:12:43,567 --> 00:12:47,800
And he had this sign
around his neck that said,

181
00:12:47,833 --> 00:12:49,667
"Why lie? I need a drink."

182
00:12:49,700 --> 00:12:50,800
I gave him 20 bucks.

183
00:12:50,833 --> 00:12:53,067
You gave a complete stranger
20 dollars?

184
00:12:53,067 --> 00:12:55,067
Yeah, but it...
it's not about the money.

185
00:12:56,267 --> 00:12:58,667
This guy was just out there

186
00:12:58,700 --> 00:13:00,333
in front of everyone.

187
00:13:01,300 --> 00:13:04,767
Just kind of... naked.

188
00:13:04,800 --> 00:13:07,133
-Naked?
-Well, not...

189
00:13:07,167 --> 00:13:10,500
Not physically naked,
just... vulnerable.

190
00:13:10,533 --> 00:13:12,333
Like he was exactly
the same on the inside

191
00:13:12,367 --> 00:13:13,867
as he is on the outside.

192
00:13:13,900 --> 00:13:16,067
He had no secrets.
He had nothing to hide.

193
00:13:16,100 --> 00:13:19,067
Did you hit your head
on the way to work today?

194
00:13:20,867 --> 00:13:22,500
What were you saying about
a gold-plated heart?

195
00:13:22,533 --> 00:13:24,467
Oh, no. I'm kidding.
I love that story.

196
00:13:24,500 --> 00:13:25,633
-Mm-hmm.
-I do.

197
00:13:25,667 --> 00:13:26,667
Let's go.

198
00:13:26,700 --> 00:13:28,067
(phone rings)

199
00:13:28,067 --> 00:13:29,767
Uh, let me get that
and I'll be there in a sec.

200
00:13:31,700 --> 00:13:32,767
Max Jordan's office.

201
00:13:32,800 --> 00:13:35,367
Man:
 What do you suggest we do, Stu?

202
00:13:35,400 --> 00:13:38,133
Don't pay out on the Shane
account and stall on the loan.

203
00:13:38,167 --> 00:13:40,800
I've crunched the numbers.
This is the best that I can do.

204
00:13:40,833 --> 00:13:42,533
Well, crunch 'em again.

205
00:13:45,500 --> 00:13:46,633
As for you,

206
00:13:46,667 --> 00:13:48,400
you'd better
come through on Russo.

207
00:13:48,433 --> 00:13:50,500
Now, we all know you've been
through a hell of an ordeal

208
00:13:50,533 --> 00:13:51,833
the last few days,

209
00:13:51,867 --> 00:13:55,667
but to close this deal
I need you at 200 percent.

210
00:13:55,700 --> 00:13:56,833
Well,
I'm having dinner with him

211
00:13:56,867 --> 00:13:58,833
in a couple nights.
I'm sure I'll sign him.

212
00:13:58,867 --> 00:14:00,067
(knocking on door)

213
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:02,267
Oh, good.
Come on in, sweetheart.

214
00:14:02,300 --> 00:14:03,267
Have a seat.

215
00:14:04,767 --> 00:14:07,633
Max, I want you
to take Scarlett along.

216
00:14:09,433 --> 00:14:10,567
Excuse me?

217
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:12,633
Take her along
to this Russo dinner.

218
00:14:16,433 --> 00:14:18,500
She's a good looking girl.
Russo's a pig.

219
00:14:18,533 --> 00:14:20,500
I think he'd appreciate
a little eye candy.

220
00:14:20,533 --> 00:14:22,233
He'll go gaga over her.

221
00:14:22,267 --> 00:14:24,100
Don't worry.
It'll be fun.

222
00:14:24,133 --> 00:14:26,167
And with the money
we make off Russo,

223
00:14:26,200 --> 00:14:28,867
I'll be able to bring Stu up
on sexual harassment charges.

224
00:14:28,900 --> 00:14:30,733
(laughs)

225
00:14:31,600 --> 00:14:32,767
Max: You know
I stand to bring in

226
00:14:32,800 --> 00:14:34,233
a couple million bucks
for this company.

227
00:14:34,267 --> 00:14:36,467
What is he talking about
200 percent?

228
00:14:38,267 --> 00:14:39,433
Didn't you get the memo?

229
00:14:43,333 --> 00:14:44,667
Look, nobody knows about this

230
00:14:44,700 --> 00:14:46,767
but we got about three months
of operating costs left

231
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:48,900
-in our account.
-What are you talking about?

232
00:14:48,933 --> 00:14:51,800
Every deal Stu has gotten us
into has tanked.

233
00:14:51,833 --> 00:14:54,967
I can't tell you how much we
lost on the Marina deal alone.

234
00:14:55,067 --> 00:14:58,067
Look, I don't want to be
the bearer of bad news.

235
00:14:58,067 --> 00:14:59,633
But if you don't pull out Russo,

236
00:14:59,667 --> 00:15:01,800
we're gonna be
on the streets by June.

237
00:15:03,067 --> 00:15:04,133
-But--
-Hey, listen. Listen.

238
00:15:04,167 --> 00:15:04,767
Come here.

239
00:15:05,933 --> 00:15:08,600
Don't feel the pressure.
I got faith in you. All right?

240
00:15:19,333 --> 00:15:20,433
Woman (over phone):
 ICU.

241
00:15:20,467 --> 00:15:22,933
Olivia Jordan for Ruth Jordan.

242
00:15:22,967 --> 00:15:26,700
(door buzzes)

243
00:15:33,467 --> 00:15:37,233
(monitor bleeps steadily)

244
00:15:37,267 --> 00:15:38,867
(air pumping)

245
00:15:53,933 --> 00:15:54,900
Hello...

246
00:15:59,700 --> 00:16:00,633
How are you?

247
00:16:01,667 --> 00:16:03,833
Don't think for a second
that I'd let a day go by

248
00:16:03,867 --> 00:16:05,933
without us doing
the crossword puzzle together.

249
00:16:07,833 --> 00:16:09,100
Let's see...

250
00:16:09,133 --> 00:16:10,900
One across.

251
00:16:10,933 --> 00:16:14,800
Three letter word for
"the ancient god of fertility."

252
00:16:14,833 --> 00:16:16,067
What do you think?

253
00:16:16,067 --> 00:16:17,433
(silence)

254
00:16:18,467 --> 00:16:20,133
That's what I thought.

255
00:16:20,167 --> 00:16:22,067
Okay.
Fourteen across.

256
00:16:22,700 --> 00:16:24,067
"Rayed flower."

257
00:16:25,300 --> 00:16:28,133
(holds back tears)
Um, five letters.

258
00:16:30,067 --> 00:16:31,167
(sighs)

259
00:17:09,333 --> 00:17:11,367
Max: I went by Aunt Ruth's 
 and Uncle Len's.

260
00:17:11,400 --> 00:17:14,133
Olivia: Why didn't you call me?
I would have met you there.

261
00:17:14,167 --> 00:17:15,633
What would you say if I told you

262
00:17:15,667 --> 00:17:17,733
I wanted to start looking for
another job?

263
00:17:17,767 --> 00:17:20,233
Maybe start my own business
with Jackson?

264
00:17:20,267 --> 00:17:21,600
Wow.
Are you serious?

265
00:17:21,633 --> 00:17:24,533
Yes. Yes, I'm very serious.

266
00:17:24,567 --> 00:17:26,733
I've... I don't think I can work
for Stu Fishman anymore.

267
00:17:26,767 --> 00:17:30,633
I mean, he screws up, we fix it.
We'd be better off on our own.

268
00:17:30,667 --> 00:17:31,567
Honey...

269
00:17:32,600 --> 00:17:34,767
Are you sure you're not
overreacting to things?

270
00:17:34,800 --> 00:17:36,667
No. I'm not gonna do
anything drastic.

271
00:17:36,700 --> 00:17:38,200
It's just that
I wanna get on with it.

272
00:17:38,233 --> 00:17:40,200
I wanna make
every minute count.

273
00:17:41,667 --> 00:17:43,067
You know,
you're all I have left...

274
00:17:44,733 --> 00:17:45,700
...and I love you.

275
00:17:47,467 --> 00:17:49,067
I love you, too.

276
00:17:49,967 --> 00:17:51,867
And I think
we should have children.

277
00:17:51,900 --> 00:17:52,867
What?

278
00:17:53,333 --> 00:17:54,567
I just...

279
00:17:55,667 --> 00:17:57,300
..think we should, uh,

280
00:17:57,333 --> 00:17:59,600
start thinking about
having a family.

281
00:18:01,867 --> 00:18:02,867
Do you mean that?

282
00:18:05,067 --> 00:18:06,333
I'm not sure actually.
I don't--

283
00:18:06,367 --> 00:18:07,600
No, Max! Max!

284
00:18:07,633 --> 00:18:08,967
(laughs)

285
00:18:09,067 --> 00:18:10,067
You mean that, don't you?

286
00:18:14,433 --> 00:18:15,567
Let's start now.

287
00:18:15,600 --> 00:18:17,500
-Now?
-Yes. Now.

288
00:18:17,533 --> 00:18:19,900
-I... I just got home.
-Good.

289
00:18:19,933 --> 00:18:21,567
You'd do it if you're not home?

290
00:18:21,600 --> 00:18:23,400
(both laugh)

291
00:18:23,433 --> 00:18:24,400
(groans)

292
00:18:30,967 --> 00:18:32,800
-Max: Good morning, Scarlett. 
-Scarlett: Good morning.

293
00:18:32,833 --> 00:18:34,200
I need you to make that 
 reservation

294
00:18:34,233 --> 00:18:36,067
for the Russo dinner
at eight o'clock

295
00:18:36,067 --> 00:18:38,367
-at Le Dejeuner.
-Mm, pretty swank.

296
00:18:38,400 --> 00:18:41,633
Well, only the best
for Mr. Russo.

297
00:18:42,800 --> 00:18:44,100
Listen, Scarlett,

298
00:18:44,133 --> 00:18:45,533
I know that
you don't want to do this--

299
00:18:45,567 --> 00:18:47,533
Well, we both know
you're nothing without me.

300
00:18:47,567 --> 00:18:48,867
Right.

301
00:18:48,900 --> 00:18:50,300
I didn't want to have to be
the one to say that.

302
00:18:50,333 --> 00:18:51,433
-Gotcha.
-Hey,

303
00:18:51,467 --> 00:18:52,567
before you get carried away,

304
00:18:52,600 --> 00:18:54,233
Mr. Fishstick sent you
some email.

305
00:18:54,267 --> 00:18:55,667
He's in Dallas
for a couple of days

306
00:18:55,700 --> 00:18:57,933
and he wants you to check out
a property for him.

307
00:18:57,967 --> 00:19:00,933
320 East 54th Street,
apartment 4B.

308
00:19:00,967 --> 00:19:02,200
East 54th?

309
00:19:02,233 --> 00:19:03,933
That's across the street
from my apartment.

310
00:19:03,967 --> 00:19:05,533
Said you gotta be there
at three o'clock.

311
00:19:05,567 --> 00:19:06,633
The keys are at the apartment.

312
00:19:07,600 --> 00:19:09,367
Max: That's not even
a commercial space.

313
00:19:09,400 --> 00:19:11,433
Hey, don't shoot the messenger.

314
00:19:13,200 --> 00:19:14,333
(sighs)

315
00:19:15,467 --> 00:19:16,733
I'm gonna kill him.

316
00:19:16,767 --> 00:19:18,733
When I'm done killing him,
I want you to kill him.

317
00:19:18,767 --> 00:19:19,900
Love to...

318
00:19:19,933 --> 00:19:21,567
as long as I still
get the free meal.

319
00:19:23,367 --> 00:19:24,400
(door closes)

320
00:20:00,567 --> 00:20:02,400
(siren wails in distance)

321
00:20:53,567 --> 00:20:55,300
(loud creaking)

322
00:21:08,933 --> 00:21:10,167
Hello?

323
00:21:29,333 --> 00:21:30,467
Hello?

324
00:21:35,533 --> 00:21:37,433
(siren wails in distance)

325
00:22:53,600 --> 00:22:54,933
Welcome home, Max.

326
00:22:55,833 --> 00:22:56,867
(groans)

327
00:23:00,067 --> 00:23:01,067
(clattering)

328
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:40,500
(shutter clicks)

329
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:46,433
(shutter clicking)

330
00:23:48,833 --> 00:23:50,200
Oh, I'm sorry.
Did I wake you?

331
00:23:52,200 --> 00:23:53,300
Mm...

332
00:23:55,067 --> 00:23:56,400
Nasty little bump, huh?

333
00:24:10,267 --> 00:24:11,267
Hungry?

334
00:24:14,567 --> 00:24:15,933
We gotta keep you well-fed,
you know.

335
00:24:18,667 --> 00:24:23,200
Okay, simple ground rules.

336
00:24:23,233 --> 00:24:25,067
It's kind of like
 This Is Your Life.

337
00:24:26,667 --> 00:24:28,467
Now when I take off the tape,

338
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:30,433
you're to remain
completely silent.

339
00:24:31,500 --> 00:24:35,167
If I ever hear you yell, scream,
cry or lie,

340
00:24:35,200 --> 00:24:36,933
I'll kill someone near
and dear to you.

341
00:24:38,433 --> 00:24:39,833
It's really very simple.

342
00:24:40,600 --> 00:24:41,667
Shall we begin?

343
00:24:53,133 --> 00:24:54,333
Who are you?

344
00:24:55,800 --> 00:24:56,967
I'm your brother.

345
00:24:59,800 --> 00:25:01,267
I don't have a brother.

346
00:25:01,300 --> 00:25:02,933
Well, that's what Ruth and Len
told you but they're liars.

347
00:25:02,967 --> 00:25:04,067
And that's why they're dead.

348
00:25:04,067 --> 00:25:04,767
Ruth's still alive.

349
00:25:05,733 --> 00:25:07,167
Well, that's true.
I did leave her alive.

350
00:25:07,200 --> 00:25:09,267
But she's a veg.
And I'd choose death

351
00:25:09,300 --> 00:25:10,733
over a veg any day,
wouldn't you?

352
00:25:12,333 --> 00:25:15,433
She's living on borrowed time
in a lonely hospital room

353
00:25:15,467 --> 00:25:16,700
just like I did.

354
00:25:18,333 --> 00:25:19,667
Did that sound poetic to you?

355
00:25:23,567 --> 00:25:24,800
Oh.

356
00:25:24,833 --> 00:25:26,833
This must be all
very confusing to you.

357
00:25:35,100 --> 00:25:37,467
The truth is,
I know everything about you.

358
00:25:41,700 --> 00:25:45,100
You're married to the beautiful
and gorgeous creative designer,

359
00:25:45,133 --> 00:25:45,900
Olivia.

360
00:25:46,900 --> 00:25:49,933
And what is with this
realty company, Max?

361
00:25:49,967 --> 00:25:51,533
I mean, you hate your boss,
you like your job.

362
00:25:51,567 --> 00:25:52,933
I mean, the things
that I've watched...

363
00:25:54,333 --> 00:25:57,233
Still, you live in a beautiful
apartment across the street.

364
00:26:00,600 --> 00:26:01,767
I know who your friends are.

365
00:26:01,800 --> 00:26:03,067
(photo hits floor)

366
00:26:04,100 --> 00:26:05,200
What you like to drink.

367
00:26:05,233 --> 00:26:06,333
(photo hits floor)

368
00:26:07,200 --> 00:26:09,067
What you like to eat.

369
00:26:09,067 --> 00:26:10,300
(photo hits floor)

370
00:26:10,333 --> 00:26:12,300
And how much money
is in that checking account.

371
00:26:12,333 --> 00:26:13,433
(photo hits floor)

372
00:26:14,067 --> 00:26:15,233
How do you know all this?

373
00:26:16,233 --> 00:26:19,933
Because I'm good, Max.
I'm very, very good.

374
00:26:19,967 --> 00:26:21,333
But as good as I am,
there's still some things

375
00:26:21,367 --> 00:26:22,600
I don't know about.

376
00:26:22,633 --> 00:26:24,100
See, that's where you come in.

377
00:26:24,133 --> 00:26:27,633
You're gonna tell me all the
intimate details of your life.

378
00:26:27,667 --> 00:26:29,333
Hell, we got a lot of
catching up to do!

379
00:26:33,200 --> 00:26:34,700
You know, it really is
good to see you.

380
00:26:35,767 --> 00:26:37,900
Now, question number one.

381
00:26:39,400 --> 00:26:42,067
What's on the Jordan schedule
for tonight?

382
00:26:57,367 --> 00:26:59,200
-(gasps)
-(laughs)

383
00:26:59,233 --> 00:27:01,067
You almost gave me
a heart attack.

384
00:27:01,100 --> 00:27:03,733
-I'm sorry. Sorry...
-(chuckling)

385
00:27:03,767 --> 00:27:04,933
Hey, where's the wine?

386
00:27:04,967 --> 00:27:06,400
-Oh, the wine!
-Max!

387
00:27:06,433 --> 00:27:07,533
I forgot. I'm sorry.

388
00:27:07,567 --> 00:27:09,067
-I completely forgot.
-That's all right.

389
00:27:09,067 --> 00:27:10,800
We'll pick some up on
the way downtown.

390
00:27:14,067 --> 00:27:15,233
I'll be ready in a minute.

391
00:27:25,433 --> 00:27:26,833
Steven (as Max): Come on. 
 Let's have a little wine,

392
00:27:26,867 --> 00:27:28,267
-shall we? 
-Jackson: A lot of wine.

393
00:27:28,300 --> 00:27:29,400
-This is really good--
-Thank you--

394
00:27:29,433 --> 00:27:30,533
What is it?

395
00:27:30,567 --> 00:27:32,333
I think this is called... white.

396
00:27:32,367 --> 00:27:34,367
-Oh, Max--
-Ever the connoisseur.

397
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:36,200
Honey, would you
make the toast please...

398
00:27:36,233 --> 00:27:37,533
Sure.

399
00:27:37,567 --> 00:27:39,100
To the two of you
leaving Chariot

400
00:27:39,133 --> 00:27:40,733
and starting your own agency.

401
00:27:44,333 --> 00:27:46,067
(chuckles nervously)
Excuse me?

402
00:27:48,433 --> 00:27:50,633
Did you forget to
tell me something, Jacks?

403
00:27:50,667 --> 00:27:51,667
(sighs)

404
00:27:51,700 --> 00:27:53,300
I guess you
didn't tell them yet.

405
00:27:53,333 --> 00:27:54,567
That would be correct.

406
00:27:54,600 --> 00:27:56,333
Ah. Well, here's to
world peace then--

407
00:27:56,367 --> 00:27:58,367
Oh, not so fast.

408
00:27:59,067 --> 00:28:00,900
When did this come about?

409
00:28:00,933 --> 00:28:02,433
Just something
I've been thinking about.

410
00:28:03,633 --> 00:28:06,633
Well, I think it's a great idea.
Stu Fishman is a disaster.

411
00:28:06,667 --> 00:28:07,800
Hear, hear!

412
00:28:07,833 --> 00:28:08,833
-Woo!
-What do ya think?

413
00:28:09,867 --> 00:28:11,067
Uh...

414
00:28:11,100 --> 00:28:12,367
I don't know what to think.

415
00:28:13,633 --> 00:28:15,733
Well, let's let Jacks have his
little breakdown and, uh,

416
00:28:15,767 --> 00:28:17,433
you and I can
go do some girlie things.

417
00:28:21,067 --> 00:28:22,267
Tess:
It's gonna be fine, Jackson.

418
00:28:22,300 --> 00:28:23,433
Steven: Jackson...

419
00:28:23,467 --> 00:28:25,067
Tess: I brought something
special for you.

420
00:28:25,067 --> 00:28:26,800
Now, let me understand this.

421
00:28:26,833 --> 00:28:30,067
You want to leave Chariot
and start our own company?

422
00:28:30,067 --> 00:28:31,300
If I sign Russo...

423
00:28:32,767 --> 00:28:34,567
-...he goes where we go.
-Russo is--

424
00:28:34,600 --> 00:28:35,833
is one guy!

425
00:28:35,867 --> 00:28:37,500
I mean, it's
a little risky starting

426
00:28:37,533 --> 00:28:38,667
a company with one client.

427
00:28:38,700 --> 00:28:39,867
We won't though.

428
00:28:40,467 --> 00:28:41,767
Don't you think that

429
00:28:41,800 --> 00:28:44,067
the clients that you've
established are gonna follow you

430
00:28:44,067 --> 00:28:46,100
if you open your own place?

431
00:28:46,133 --> 00:28:48,167
Jacks, think about all the work
you've put in.

432
00:28:48,200 --> 00:28:50,067
Now, how many years
have you been there now?

433
00:28:50,100 --> 00:28:51,867
-Eight.
-Exactly, eight years.

434
00:28:51,900 --> 00:28:53,300
I've been there five.
It's time that--

435
00:28:53,333 --> 00:28:54,533
-Four.
-Four, five--

436
00:28:54,567 --> 00:28:56,067
It feels like a lifetime
and you know it.

437
00:28:57,400 --> 00:28:58,467
Jacks...

438
00:29:02,067 --> 00:29:03,833
Do you want to work for
Stu Fishman

439
00:29:03,867 --> 00:29:05,133
for the rest of your life?

440
00:29:07,533 --> 00:29:08,667
What do ya think?

441
00:29:11,533 --> 00:29:12,733
I think it's crazy...

442
00:29:14,133 --> 00:29:16,067
...but I wish
I would've thought of it.

443
00:29:16,067 --> 00:29:17,600
(chuckling)

444
00:29:17,633 --> 00:29:18,900
Oh, I wanna warn you.

445
00:29:18,933 --> 00:29:20,433
It's "halibut a la Jackson."

446
00:29:20,467 --> 00:29:21,600
Oh...

447
00:29:23,500 --> 00:29:26,067
Boy, Max sure seems
in a good mood tonight.

448
00:29:26,067 --> 00:29:27,800
I thought we'd have to spend
the evening cheering him up.

449
00:29:27,833 --> 00:29:29,800
Olivia: I don't know
what's gotten into him.

450
00:29:29,833 --> 00:29:31,833
Mm, well, who knows?

451
00:29:31,867 --> 00:29:34,667
A month from now it could hit
him like a ton of bricks.

452
00:29:34,700 --> 00:29:36,600
Then he'll get into that lovely

453
00:29:36,633 --> 00:29:41,067
"anger, bargaining,
depression, guilt..."

454
00:29:41,067 --> 00:29:42,767
I can hardly wait.

455
00:29:42,800 --> 00:29:43,867
Tess: Well,

456
00:29:43,900 --> 00:29:45,400
you just let him go
at his own pace.

457
00:29:45,433 --> 00:29:47,900
You prepare yourself
'cause it's gonna rock him.

458
00:29:47,933 --> 00:29:51,067
(Steven and Max
chattering)

459
00:29:55,233 --> 00:29:57,400
(gasping, groaning)

460
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:16,033
You okay?

461
00:30:16,967 --> 00:30:18,000
Yeah.

462
00:30:18,033 --> 00:30:19,633
(siren wails in distance)

463
00:30:19,667 --> 00:30:20,767
Are you okay?

464
00:30:21,533 --> 00:30:22,900
Yeah, why wouldn't I be?

465
00:30:24,033 --> 00:30:25,267
I don't know.

466
00:30:26,500 --> 00:30:27,633
It was just...

467
00:30:28,467 --> 00:30:29,767
very intense.

468
00:30:31,900 --> 00:30:33,667
Good intense or bad intense?

469
00:30:33,700 --> 00:30:34,933
(exhales)

470
00:30:36,567 --> 00:30:38,200
Good intense.

471
00:30:38,233 --> 00:30:39,533
Definitely...

472
00:30:39,567 --> 00:30:41,100
Definitely good intense.

473
00:30:42,667 --> 00:30:43,967
It must've been the wine.

474
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:48,367
In that case,

475
00:30:48,400 --> 00:30:50,500
you better pick up
a lot for next weekend.

476
00:30:50,533 --> 00:30:53,367
(panting)
(chuckling)

477
00:30:59,900 --> 00:31:01,333
(groaning)

478
00:31:21,100 --> 00:31:22,467
(grunting)

479
00:31:27,333 --> 00:31:30,067
(struggling)

480
00:31:33,567 --> 00:31:35,900
(breathes heavily)

481
00:32:18,433 --> 00:32:19,433
(bleep)

482
00:32:21,233 --> 00:32:22,400
(bleep)

483
00:32:22,967 --> 00:32:24,767
(ringing)

484
00:32:25,633 --> 00:32:26,800
Hi, honey.

485
00:32:26,833 --> 00:32:29,067
(muffled groans)

486
00:32:30,133 --> 00:32:31,333
Max?

487
00:32:31,367 --> 00:32:32,867
-(bleeping)
-Olivia: Is that you? Max?

488
00:32:32,900 --> 00:32:34,267
(muffled groans)

489
00:32:34,300 --> 00:32:35,467
(bleeping)

490
00:32:35,500 --> 00:32:36,767
(muffled groaning)

491
00:32:36,800 --> 00:32:38,067
-Max...?
-(line goes dead)

492
00:32:45,300 --> 00:32:47,467
(phone ringing)

493
00:32:48,767 --> 00:32:50,133
Max Jordan's office.

494
00:32:50,167 --> 00:32:51,867
Olivia: Scarlett, is Max in?

495
00:32:51,900 --> 00:32:54,333
Oh yeah, hon. He's right here.
Just a sec.

496
00:32:54,367 --> 00:32:55,467
(buzzer)

497
00:32:59,367 --> 00:33:00,667
(bleep)

498
00:33:00,700 --> 00:33:01,667
Hi.

499
00:33:01,700 --> 00:33:03,400
Olivia:
 Why'd you hang up on me?

500
00:33:03,433 --> 00:33:04,333
Hang up on you?

501
00:33:05,267 --> 00:33:07,067
Well, I just got a call
on my private line

502
00:33:07,100 --> 00:33:08,867
but they hung up.
So I assumed it was you.

503
00:33:10,067 --> 00:33:11,100
No...

504
00:33:12,067 --> 00:33:13,300
No, it wasn't me.

505
00:33:13,333 --> 00:33:15,267
Ah, it must've been
a wrong number.

506
00:33:15,300 --> 00:33:18,233
So, what are you
doing right now?

507
00:33:18,267 --> 00:33:20,133
Besides thinking about
last night, nothing much.

508
00:33:20,167 --> 00:33:21,600
-Why?
-Well,

509
00:33:21,633 --> 00:33:23,933
I had a buyer cancel on me
so I have the afternoon free.

510
00:33:23,967 --> 00:33:25,767
Steven: The afternoon free...

511
00:33:25,800 --> 00:33:28,533
(clicks tongue)
Mm...

512
00:33:28,567 --> 00:33:31,733
Meet you back at the apartment
in 45 minutes?

513
00:33:31,767 --> 00:33:33,267
Well, actually I was thinking

514
00:33:33,300 --> 00:33:34,833
this was a really good time
for us to go to the hospital

515
00:33:34,867 --> 00:33:37,733
-to visit Aunt Ruth.
-No. No, I can't.

516
00:33:37,767 --> 00:33:40,067
Well, I thought you said 
 you had nothing to do.

517
00:33:40,067 --> 00:33:41,400
I don't.

518
00:33:41,433 --> 00:33:43,933
I do, actually.
I actually have a lot to do.

519
00:33:43,967 --> 00:33:45,800
Uh, the Russo situation
has everything, sort of,

520
00:33:45,833 --> 00:33:47,067
piled up here

521
00:33:47,067 --> 00:33:48,733
and I have to take 
 care of this this afternoon.

